---
// "The fix." — the answer to § 2's warm problem sub-section.
// Three full-width hairline-top columns, each pairing one of the named
// problems (eyebrow) with a concrete mechanism (body). Per voice-and-tone.md
// Rule 2: every fix names a verifiable mechanism, not an adjective.
---

<section class="the-fix section" id="the-fix" aria-labelledby="the-fix-title">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <h2 id="the-fix-title" class="the-fix__title">The fix.</h2>
    <p class="the-fix__lede">Each one has a specific mechanism.</p>

    <ul class="the-fix__grid">
      <li class="fix-card">
        <h3 class="fix-card__eyebrow">Specs drift</h3>
        <p class="fix-card__body">
          One canonical spec, in the repo, versioned with the code.
          <code>specscore lint</code> runs in CI on every push; the git
          history shows exactly what changed and when. The spec, the
          Slack thread, and the PR can't quietly disagree — they share
          the same file under review.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li class="fix-card">
        <h3 class="fix-card__eyebrow">AC stay vague</h3>
        <p class="fix-card__body">
          The linter catches ambiguous criteria before any code is
          written. <em>"Handles errors gracefully"</em> fails lint
          because the verb has no concrete object or condition. Fixing
          the warning forces you to write what <em>"handles"</em>
          actually means — toast-and-roll-back, or log-and-retry.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li class="fix-card">
        <h3 class="fix-card__eyebrow">Agents ship the wrong thing</h3>
        <p class="fix-card__body">
          The format is structured input. AI agents parse REQ IDs, AC IDs
          and <code>GIVEN&nbsp;/&nbsp;WHEN&nbsp;/&nbsp;THEN</code>
          scenarios deterministically — there's nothing to interpolate.
          Plans must cite the AC IDs each task satisfies, so what was
          built is always checkable against what was specified.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<style>
  /* --cream (not --cream-2) — the page reserves --cream-2 for the
     attention-grabbing on-ramp (AiSkills) and FinalCta. TheFix is
     paired with § 2 (problem → answer), so it shares § 2's --cream. */
  .the-fix { background: var(--cream); }

  .the-fix__title {
    font-size: var(--fs-h2);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: -0.01em;
  }
  .the-fix__lede {
    color: var(--mid-ink);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-5);
    font-size: 1.05rem;
  }

  .the-fix__grid {
    list-style: none;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
    gap: var(--space-4);
  }
  .fix-card {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--graphite);
    padding-top: var(--space-2);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
  }
  .fix-card__eyebrow {
    font-family: var(--font-code);
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: var(--graphite);
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-2);
  }
  .fix-card__body {
    color: var(--ink);
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
    margin: 0;
  }
  .fix-card__body code {
    background: var(--cream-2);
    padding: 0.05em 0.35em;
    border-radius: 2px;
    font-size: 0.92em;
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .fix-card__body em {
    font-style: normal;
    background: var(--cream-2);
    padding: 0.05em 0.35em;
    border-radius: 2px;
    font-family: var(--font-code);
    font-size: 0.9em;
    color: var(--ink);
  }

  @media (max-width: 800px) {
    .the-fix__grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: var(--space-3);
    }
  }
</style>
